<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="visibility-of-system-status">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>accessibility-specialist</domain>
    <summary>Keep users informed about system status through appropriate feedback within reasonable time so they understand if actions succeeded, failed, or are in progress.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>usability</tag>
      <tag>heuristics</tag>
      <tag>feedback</tag>
      <tag>loading</tag>
      <tag>accessibility</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>ux-design</category>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Visibility of System Status</title>

    <summary>The design must always keep users informed about what is going on through appropriate feedback within a reasonable amount of time. Without system status visibility, users click repeatedly, abandon tasks, and lose trust. Feedback for every action, timely response, clear communication, and appropriate context are the core principles.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Users click a button and nothing appears to happen. They wonder if the system is working. They click again, accidentally submitting twice. They abandon tasks because they cannot tell if progress is being made. Users feel anxious and out of control.</p>
      <p>Without system status visibility, the result is user confusion, repeated actions, abandoned tasks, and frustration and distrust. This is Nielsen's first usability heuristic: the design should always keep users informed about what is going on, through appropriate feedback within a reasonable amount of time.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any user action that triggers a server request: form submissions, file uploads, payments, deletions</item>
        <item>Long-running operations (greater than 1 second): imports, exports, report generation, AI completions</item>
        <item>Asynchronous operations where the result arrives later: email send, background job, webhook</item>
        <item>Multi-step forms where users need to know which step they are on and how many remain</item>
        <item>Real-time status changes: connection health, sync state, auto-save confirmation</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Instantaneous operations (less than 100ms) where a loading indicator would flash and disappear distractingly</item>
        <item>Background telemetry or logging operations the user has no reason to know about</item>
        <item>Internal system operations that do not affect the user's current task</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="response-time-guidelines">
      <p>Different response times require different feedback strategies. The faster feedback arrives relative to the response time, the more confident the user feels.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Less than 0.1 second: provide visual state change only (highlight, color change, immediate visual feedback).</statement>
        <rationale>User perceives action as instantaneous; explicit loading indicator is unnecessary and clutters the UI.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>0.1-1 second: show a loading indicator like a spinner with "Loading..." text.</statement>
        <rationale>User perceives system as working; spinner confirms input was received and prevents double-click.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>1-10 seconds: show a progress indicator with estimated time or percentage.</statement>
        <rationale>Wait is noticeable and user needs reassurance progress is ongoing; vague spinner creates anxiety.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Greater than 10 seconds: show a progress bar with percentage and time remaining, plus a cancel option.</statement>
        <rationale>Long operation requires detailed status to prevent abandonment; cancel option prevents user feeling trapped.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="types-of-system-status">
      <p>System status falls into five categories with distinct purposes and visual presentations.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Loading: operation in progress. Show spinners or progress bars.</statement>
        <rationale>Communicates that the system received the input and is working.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Success: action completed. Show checkmarks or success messages with confirmation text.</statement>
        <rationale>Confirms to the user that their intent was fulfilled.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Error: something went wrong. Show error messages or alerts with specific problem description.</statement>
        <rationale>Explains what failed and how to recover; vague errors cause abandonment.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Progress: multi-step process. Show step indicators, progress bars, or completion percentage.</statement>
        <rationale>Users in multi-step flows need to know location and how many steps remain.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>State: current situation. Show online/offline indicators, saved status, or connection health.</statement>
        <rationale>Persistent state indicators keep users aware of environmental conditions affecting actions.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="loading-indicators">
      <p>Different types of loading indicators serve different durations and user knowledge levels.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use a spinner for short, indeterminate waits (1-3 seconds, unknown duration) with "Loading..." text.</statement>
        <rationale>Spinners are recognizable universal symbols for "system is working"; text confirms the system has not hung.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use a progress bar for longer, measurable operations (greater than 3 seconds, known duration) showing percentage, time remaining, and a cancel option.</statement>
        <rationale>Measurable operations with duration estimates reduce user anxiety; cancel option prevents feeling trapped.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use skeleton screens for content loading to show expected layout without content.</statement>
        <rationale>Skeleton screens match content structure, reducing perceptual wait time compared to blank loading states.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="success-feedback">
      <p>Confirming successful completion prevents user uncertainty about whether action succeeded.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use inline confirmation where button changes to "Saved!" with checkmark, then returns to "Save" after dismissal.</statement>
        <rationale>Inline confirmation keeps feedback contextually adjacent to action without requiring modal or separate notification.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use toast notification for success messages that auto-dismiss after 2-4 seconds with text like "Changes saved successfully".</statement>
        <rationale>Auto-dismiss prevents notification fatigue while giving sufficient time for user to read confirmation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use page transition to confirmation page showing summary when action results in new state.</statement>
        <rationale>Page transitions clarify that action completed by showing the resulting state.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="error-feedback">
      <p>Error states must explain what went wrong and suggest recovery.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use inline validation showing error next to specific field immediately when user leaves the field.</statement>
        <rationale>Field-level errors help users locate and fix problems without scrolling.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use summary notification showing "Please fix 3 errors before continuing" with links to each error field.</statement>
        <rationale>Summary view helps users understand overall scope before attempting fixes.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="state-indicators">
      <p>Persistent state indicators keep users aware of system conditions affecting their actions.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use connection status indicators: green dot for online, yellow for connecting, red for offline with retry option.</statement>
        <rationale>Visual color coding with icons makes status immediately scannable without reading text.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use document status indicators showing "Draft" | "Saving..." | "All changes saved".</statement>
        <rationale>Document status reassures users that work is being preserved.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="implementation-patterns">
      <rule>
        <statement>Disable the submit button immediately on click and show a spinner inline in the button to prevent double submission and give instant feedback within the same element the user just interacted with.</statement>
        <rationale>Users cannot accidentally re-click a disabled button; feedback stays contextually adjacent to the action.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>For operations lasting 1-3 seconds, use an indeterminate spinner; for operations where progress can be measured (file upload, batch import), use a determinate progress bar with percentage.</statement>
        <rationale>Determinate progress indicators reduce perceived wait time for measurable operations.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Distinguish error states from loading states with color and icon — a spinner that changes to a red X with "Failed — try again" is clearer than making the spinner disappear.</statement>
        <rationale>Color and icon differentiation prevents confusion between "still loading" and "failed".</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Auto-save confirmation ("All changes saved") should appear for 2 seconds maximum and not reappear on every keystroke — debounce to show only after a pause in editing.</statement>
        <rationale>Excessive notifications create fatigue; debouncing shows confirmation only after user has paused editing.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Connection status indicators should only become visible when the connection is degraded — showing a permanent "Online" indicator trains users to ignore it.</statement>
        <rationale>Persistent visible indicators experience "banner blindness"; only show when state is problematic.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Always provide a recovery action in error states: "Retry", "Contact support", or "Go back" — a bare error message with no path forward causes abandonment.</statement>
        <rationale>Actionable recovery options prevent user abandonment when errors occur.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="File upload with detailed feedback">
        <note>Click "Upload" - button shows "Uploading..." and is disabled. Progress bar appears with percentage. File name visible with upload speed. Complete: checkmark + "Upload complete". If error: specific error message + retry button.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Form submission with state transitions">
        <note>Click "Submit" - button disabled, shows spinner. Success: green banner "Form submitted successfully". Error: red banner with specific error + form fields highlighted with inline error text next to each field.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="No feedback on click">
        <note>User clicks button. Nothing visible happens. User clicks again (duplicate submission). Eventually page changes without any explanation.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Vague status messaging">
        <note>"Please wait..." (how long?). "Processing..." (what?). Generic spinner (any progress?). No indication of how long the operation will take.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Progress bars for indeterminate-length operations are misleading; they can only be accurate for operations with known total work units.</description>
        <reason>Showing a progress bar stuck at 50% for an unknown-duration operation frustrates users who cannot estimate completion time.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Over-notification: showing a success toast for every auto-save event creates notification fatigue and users stop noticing actual errors.</description>
        <reason>Auto-save confirmation should appear only after a pause in editing and dismiss after 2 seconds maximum; excessive notifications train users to ignore them.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Skeleton screens require designing the exact expected layout in advance; they break when the content structure differs from expectations.</description>
        <reason>Skeleton screens work well for predictable layouts like article lists but mislead users on complex dynamic content where actual layout differs from skeleton.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>ARIA live regions for screen readers require careful implementation — aria-live="assertive" for errors, aria-live="polite" for non-critical updates; mixing them causes accessibility regressions.</description>
        <reason>Screen reader users rely on live regions to hear status changes; incorrect politeness levels make updates either intrusive or invisible.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Offline/online status detection via navigator.onLine is unreliable; it detects network adapter state, not actual internet connectivity.</description>
        <reason>A user can appear online to the browser but unable to reach the internet; status indicators must actually test connectivity with real API calls.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="accessibility-considerations">
      <p>System status feedback must be perceivable to all users including those using assistive technologies.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use ARIA live regions for dynamic updates so screen reader users hear status changes without needing to navigate the page.</statement>
        <rationale>Screen reader users cannot see visual loading indicators; live regions announce status changes automatically.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Do not rely solely on color for status; always pair color with text, icons, or patterns.</statement>
        <rationale>Color-blind users and those with monochrome displays cannot distinguish status by color alone.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Provide text alternatives for icons representing status.</statement>
        <rationale>Icon meanings are not universally understood; text ensures intent is clear to all users.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Allow users to dismiss notifications so they do not trap attention.</statement>
        <rationale>Some users navigate using keyboard or voice; undismissable notifications trap focus permanently.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <p>Recurring errors that degrade user experience and accessibility.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never show no loading indicator for button clicks that trigger server requests.</statement>
        <rationale>Users assume the click did not register and click again, causing duplicate submissions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never delay feedback for more than 2 seconds after user action.</statement>
        <rationale>Users perceive delays greater than 2 seconds as unresponsiveness.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never show error messages without specific context about what failed or how to fix it.</statement>
        <rationale>Generic "Error occurred" messages force users to guess the cause and provide no recovery path.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always define error states in the prototype or spec so implementation cannot be accidental.</statement>
        <rationale>Error states are frequently omitted in development because they are not visible in happy-path testing.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never overload feedback with too many simultaneous notifications.</statement>
        <rationale>Multiple notifications compete for attention and confuse users about which notification is most urgent.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="verification-checklist">
      <p>A comprehensive checklist for validating visibility-of-system-status implementation.</p>
      <checklist>
        <check>Every clickable element provides immediate feedback</check>
        <check>Loading states are visible for operations greater than 0.5 seconds</check>
        <check>Progress indicators show for operations greater than 3 seconds</check>
        <check>Success states confirm action completion</check>
        <check>Error states explain what went wrong</check>
        <check>Current state (online/offline, saved/unsaved) is visible</check>
        <check>ARIA live regions announce status changes to screen readers</check>
        <check>Status feedback does not rely solely on color</check>
        <check>Icons have text alternatives</check>
        <check>Users can dismiss notifications</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="measurement">
      <p>Quantifiable metrics for evaluating visibility-of-system-status implementation.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Track task completion rate as percentage of users completing tasks — increases when feedback is clear.</statement>
        <rationale>Completion rate is the most direct measure of whether users understand the system status.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Track repeated clicks on the same button during loading — users re-click when they see no feedback.</statement>
        <rationale>Duplicate submissions indicate missing or delayed feedback.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Track abandonment during loading — users leaving during operations indicate too-long waits or vague status.</statement>
        <rationale>Abandonment patterns reveal which operations need better feedback or faster execution.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Monitor support tickets containing "Is it working?" — high volume indicates widespread status visibility failure.</statement>
        <rationale>Users should never need to contact support to determine if an action succeeded.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>How Claude subagents can audit and implement system status patterns.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Claude subagents can audit component code or UI descriptions for missing feedback states and generate implementation specs for loading, success, error, and progress patterns.</statement>
        <rationale>The audit step is fully automatable through code analysis or UI description parsing.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Agents can also write the specific component code (React spinner, toast notification, ARIA live region) given a component spec and library context.</statement>
        <rationale>Implementation is mechanical pattern application once the spec is clear.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Human review is required for timing decisions (when to show, when to dismiss) that depend on UX context.</statement>
        <rationale>Timing is a design judgment call that depends on content context and user attention patterns, not a mechanical choice.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="tools-and-cli">
      <p>Command-line tools and services that support system status implementation and validation.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use axe-core CLI to detect missing ARIA live regions and role violations in components.</statement>
        <rationale>Automated accessibility scanning catches ARIA implementation gaps before user testing.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use pa11y for automated scans including ARIA status violations across entire pages.</statement>
        <rationale>Page-level scanning reveals accessibility issues in the full context, not isolated components.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use Playwright to test loading states and state transitions in CI to prevent regressions.</statement>
        <rationale>Automated interaction testing catches missing feedback states before production.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use Storybook to visualize all status states (loading/error/success) in isolation for manual review.</statement>
        <rationale>Storybook provides a gallery of states for designers to audit completeness before implementation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Run Lighthouse CI to measure perceived performance including loading feedback quality.</statement>
        <rationale>Lighthouse metrics correlate with user perception of speed and responsiveness.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/visibility-system-status/"/>
      <link href="https://m3.material.io/components/progress-indicators/overview"/>
